maize-94: cast char/unsigned-char pointer mismatches in the POSIX character-class
matcher so the strict cproc-qbe front end accepts them.

Upstream file/function: misc.c (posix_cclass, cclass). Why: oksh's glob/case pattern
matcher walks patterns as `const unsigned char *`, but hands those pointers to the
`char *`-typed strchr/strncmp and to posix_cclass. The pinned cproc-qbe is strict
about pointer signedness (it rejects the char/unsigned-char mix that gcc merely warns
on under -Wpointer-sign), so the call sites are given explicit casts. This is a pure
type-annotation change: no runtime behavior differs (the bytes and the ASCII class
names are unchanged), it only spells the conversions the C standard requires
explicitly. Type erasure is NOT introduced: the casts are between concrete pointer
types at the call sites, keeping the typed prototypes intact.
